{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583748"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:27:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:27:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13695"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13695"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6311"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112294"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6311"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13695"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1443"},{"type":"tags","id":"3557"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8387"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14651"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45950"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112294","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112294"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of irritability and fever. His parent reports he has been pulling at his left ear and refusing to eat. He has no significant medical history, does not take any regular medications, and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Otoscopy of the right ear is seen in image 1. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would be most concerning and require urgent hospital admission?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bilateral tympanic membrane involvement","Post-auricular tenderness and swelling","Temperature greater than 39\u00b0C","Purulent discharge from the ear canal","Cervical lymphadenopathy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute otitis media is a common childhood infection that can occasionally lead to serious complications requiring urgent intervention. While most cases can be managed in the community, certain clinical findings indicate potential complications that necessitate immediate hospital admission and specialist assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-auricular tenderness and swelling\u003C/strong\u003E are classic signs of mastoiditis, a serious complication of acute otitis media where infection spreads to the mastoid air cells. This represents extension of infection beyond the middle ear and requires urgent hospital admission for intravenous antibiotics and potential surgical drainage. Mastoiditis can progress to intracranial complications if not treated promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral tympanic membrane involvement\u003C/strong\u003E indicates bilateral acute otitis media, which while more extensive than unilateral disease, does not necessarily require hospital admission in an otherwise well child. It can typically be managed with appropriate oral antibiotics and close follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemperature greater than 39\u00b0C\u003C/strong\u003E is concerning but not an absolute indication for admission in acute otitis media unless accompanied by other red flag features. High fever alone in a child who is otherwise responding appropriately can often be managed in the community with appropriate antibiotics and antipyretics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPurulent discharge from the ear canal\u003C/strong\u003E suggests tympanic membrane perforation, which can actually provide relief of symptoms by allowing drainage of middle ear contents. While this requires follow-up to ensure healing, it does not typically necessitate hospital admission unless there are other concerning features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical lymphadenopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a common finding in children with ear infections and represents a normal immune response to local infection. This finding alone would not warrant hospital admission unless the lymph nodes were extremely enlarged or there were signs of suppuration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-auricular tenderness and swelling are key clinical signs of mastoiditis, a serious complication of acute otitis media.","Mastoiditis requires urgent hospital admission for intravenous antibiotics and potential surgical intervention.","Red flags in acute otitis media include post-auricular signs, facial nerve palsy, altered consciousness, and signs of intracranial complications."],"references":["Acute Otitis Media. In: Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Clinical Practice Guidelines [online]. 2021 [cited 2024 Jun]. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Acute_otitis_media/","Harmes KM, Blackwood RA, Burrows HL, Cooke JM, Harrison RV, Passamani PP. Otitis media: diagnosis and treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2013 Oct 1;88(7):435-40. Erratum in: Am Fam Physician. 2014 Mar 1;89(5):318. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2013/1001/p435.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13695"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20930"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20930"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6lCoVPDkTTUIcpmWmJZHJsxf78Oakq.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6lCoVPDkTTUIcpmWmJZHJsxf78Oakq.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":471,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-28T13:15:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-28T13:17:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6311"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112294"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":